        <div class="row-start-1 md:row-span-3">
            <p class="lg:text-xl pb-4">Finally we have an approved suite of mockups. Time to move to our component library. I fire up Storybook, VSCode and start building out the composite React components. We're using flexbox to layout the panel rows and columns within. I'm creating the main accordion panel with the supplementary panels <em>only</em> if there information that necessitates a supplementary panel. I collaborate with the backend engineer about data structures to ensure the API is flexible. A lot of this is rebuilding the high fidelity mockups from our design application in Storybook form so we can see the parallel design come alive and also because we know it's a practical example data set.</p>
            <p class="lg:text-xl pb-4">There are a couple pitfalls of using flexbox. The main one is that you have to be more manual about different rows and their column alignment. CSS grid would solve this but technically is not applicable to this situation. Another issue is how the layout breaks. When there is too much information and elements on the screen, on smaller devices, something is going to give. Instead of breaking to a new line causing more height in the overall UI I setup these components to push off to the right. We aim for this to never happen but were pleased with how graceful it fails. </p>
            <p class="lg:text-xl pb-4">Once things are at 80% I ship a version of our component library with this <code>AccordionList</code> React component and it's children components. The backend developer consumes these and starts building out in our app on their local build environment. This is where we discuss what works and what needs to be modified or added. This gives me time to clean up imperative code that can be more declarative, finalize lower priority functionality and write proper JSDocs.</p>
        </div>
    </section>
